* Rounding this out where applicable is {{lang|und-Deva|ळ}} ''{{IAST|ḷa}}'' ([[International Phonetic Alphabet|IPA]]: {{IPA|/ɭ/}}or {{IPA|/ɭ̆/}}), the intervocalic [[retroflex lateral flap|lateral flap]] allophone of the [[voiced retroflex stop]] in [[Vedic Sanskrit]], which is a [[phoneme]] in languages such as [[Marathi language|Marathi]], [[Konkani language|Konkani]], and [[Rajasthani language|Rajasthani]].<ref>Masica (1991:97)</ref>
* Beyond the Sanskritic set, new shapes have rarely been formulated. {{Harvcoltxt|Masica|1991|p=146}} offers the following, "In any case, according to some, all possible sounds had already been described and provided for in this system, as Sanskrit was the original and perfect language. Hence it was difficult to provide for or even to conceive ''other'' sounds, unknown to the [[phonetician]]s of Sanskrit". Where foreign borrowings and internal developments did inevitably accrue and arise in New Indo-Aryan languages, they have been ignored in writing, or dealt through means such as [[diacritic]]s and [[Typographic ligature|ligatures]] (ignored in recitation).
** The most prolific diacritic has been the [[subscript]] dot (''[[Nukta|nuqtā]]'') <span style="font-size:14pt;">{{lang|und-Deva|़}}</span>. [[Hindi]] uses it for the [[Persian language|Persian]], [[Arabic language|Arabic]] and English sounds <span style="font-size:14pt;">{{lang|hi|[[क़]]}}</span> ''qa'' [[Voiceless uvular plosive|/q/]], <span style="font-size:14pt;">{{lang|hi|[[ख़]]}}</span> ''xa'' [[Voiceless velar fricative|/x/]], <span style="font-size:14pt;">{{lang|hi|[[ग़]]}}</span> ''ġa'' [[Voiced velar fricative|/ɣ/]], <span style="font-size:14pt;">{{lang|hi|[[ज़]]}}</span> ''za'' [[Voiced alveolar fricative|/z/]], <span style="font-size:14pt;">{{lang|hi|[[झ़]]}}</span> ''zha'' [[Voiced postalveolar fricative|/ʒ/]], and <span style="font-size:14pt;">{{lang|hi|[[फ़]]}}</span> ''fa'' [[Voiceless labiodental fricative|/f/]], and for the [[allophonic]] developments <span style="font-size:14pt;">{{lang|hi|[[ड़]]}}</span> ''{{IAST|ṛa}}'' [[Retroflex flap|/ɽ/]] and <span style="font-size:14pt;">{{lang|hi|[[ढ़]]}}</span> ''{{IAST|ṛha}}'' /ɽʱ/. (Although <span style="font-size:14pt;">{{lang|hi|ऴ}}</span> ''{{IAST|ḷha}}'' {{IPA|/ɭʱä/}} could also exist, it is not used in Hindi.)
** [[Sindhi language|Sindhi]]'s and [[Saraiki dialect|Saraiki]]'s [[implosive]]s are accommodated with a line attached below: <span style="font-size:14pt;">{{lang|sd-Deva|[[Voiced velar implosive|ॻ]]}}</span> {{IPA|[ɠə]}}, <span style="font-size:14pt;">{{lang|sd-Deva|[[Voiced palatal implosive|ॼ]]}}</span> {{IPA|[ʄə]}}, <span style="font-size:14pt;">{{lang|sd-Deva|[[Voiced alveolar implosive|ॾ]]}}</span> {{IPA|[ɗə]}}, <span style="font-size:14pt;">{{lang|sd-Deva|[[Voiced bilabial implosive|ॿ]]}}</span> {{IPA|[ɓə]}}.
** [[Aspiration (phonetics)|Aspirated]] [[sonorant]]s may be represented as conjuncts/[[Typographic ligature|ligatures]] with <span style="font-size:14pt;">{{lang|und-Deva|ह}}</span> ''ha'': <span style="font-size:14pt;">{{lang|und-Deva|म्ह}}</span> ''mha'', <span style="font-size:14pt;">{{lang|und-Deva|न्ह}}</span> ''nha'', <span style="font-size:14pt;">{{lang|und-Deva|ण्ह}}</span> ''{{IAST|ṇha}}'', <span style="font-size:14pt;">{{lang|und-Deva|व्ह}}</span> ''vha'', <span style="font-size:14pt;">{{lang|und-Deva|ल्ह}}</span> ''lha'', <span style="font-size:14pt;">{{lang|und-Deva|ळ्ह}}</span> ''{{IAST|ḷha}}'', <span style="font-size:14pt;">{{lang|und-Deva|र्ह}}</span> ''rha''.
** {{Harvcoltxt|Masica|1991|p=147}} notes [[Marwari language|Marwari]] as using {{lang|mwr-Deva|ॸ}} for ''{{IAST|ḍa}}'' {{IPA|[ɗə]}} (while {{lang|mwr-Deva|ड}} represents {{IPA|[ɽə]}}).
