A vowel combines with a consonant to form their compound letter. For example, the vowel {{lang|hi|आ}} ({{transl|hi|ISO|ā}}) combines with the consonant {{lang|hi|क्}} ({{transl|hi|ISO|k}}) to form the compound {{lang|hi|का}} ({{transl|hi|ISO|kā}}), with halant removed and added vowel sign which is indicated by [[diacritic]]s. The vowel {{lang|hi|अ}} ({{transl|hi|ISO|a}}) combines with the consonant {{lang|hi|क्}} ({{transl|hi|ISO|k}}) to form the compound {{lang|hi|क}} ({{transl|hi|ISO|ka}}) with halant removed. But, the compound letter series of {{lang|hi|क, ख, ग, घ}} ... ({{transl|hi|ISO|ka, kha, ga, gha}}) is without any added vowel sign, as the vowel अ (a) is [[Inherent vowel|inherent]].

===Conjunct consonants===
[[File:1765 Saka, 1843 CE, Jnanesvari Jnandeva Dnyaneshwar manuscript page 1 and 2, Devanagari Marathi.jpg|thumb|upright=1.25| The ''Jnanesvari'' is a commentary on the ''[[Bhagavad Gita]]'', dated to 1290 CE. It is in Devanagari script, Marathi language.]]
As mentioned, successive consonants lacking a vowel in between them may physically join together as a ''[[conjunct consonant]]'' or [[Ligature (typography)|ligature]]. Conjuncts are used mostly with loan words. Native words typically use the basic consonant and native speakers know to suppress the vowel. For example, the native Hindi word ''karnā'' is written {{lang|und-Deva|करना}} (''ka-ra-nā'').<ref>Saloman, Richard (2007) “Typological Observations on the Indic Scripts” in ''The Indic Scripts: Paleographic and Linguistic Perspecticves'' D.K. Printworld Ltd., New Delhi. {{ISBN|812460406-1}}. p. 33.</ref> The government of these clusters ranges from widely to narrowly applicable rules, with special exceptions within. While standardised for the most part, there are certain variations in clustering, of which the [[Unicode]] used on this page is just one scheme. The following are a number of rules:
* 24 out of the 36 consonants contain a vertical right stroke (<span style="font-size:14pt;">{{lang|und-Deva|ख}}</span> ''kha'', <span style="font-size:14pt;">{{lang|und-Deva|घ}}</span> ''gha'', <span style="font-size:14pt;">{{lang|und-Deva|ण}}</span> ''ṇa'' etc.). As first or middle fragments/members of a cluster, they lose that stroke. e.g. <span style="font-size:14pt;">{{lang|und-Deva|त}}</span> + <span style="font-size:14pt;">{{lang|und-Deva|व}}</span> = <span style="font-size:14pt;">{{lang|und-Deva|त्व}}</span> ''tva'', <span style="font-size:14pt;">{{lang|und-Deva|ण}}</span> + <span style="font-size:14pt;">{{lang|und-Deva|ढ}}</span> = <span style="font-size:14pt;">{{lang|und-Deva|ण्ढ}}</span> ''ṇḍha'', <span style="font-size:14pt;">{{lang|und-Deva|स}}</span> + <span style="font-size:14pt;">{{lang|und-Deva|थ}}</span> = <span style="font-size:14pt;">{{lang|und-Deva|स्थ}}</span> ''stha''. In Unicode, these consonants without their vertical stems are called half forms.<ref name="Unicode ch. 9">{{cite web|title=The Unicode Standard, chapter 9, South Asian Scripts I|url=https://www.unicode.org/versions/Unicode6.0.0/ch09.pdf|work=The Unicode Standard, v. 6.0|publisher=Unicode, Inc|accessdate=Feb 12, 2012}}</ref>  <span style="font-size:14pt;">{{lang|und-Deva|श}}</span> ''ś(a)'' appears as a different, simple ribbon-shaped fragment preceding <span style="font-size:14pt;">{{lang|und-Deva|व}}</span> ''va'', <span style="font-size:14pt;">{{lang|und-Deva|न}}</span> ''na'', <span style="font-size:14pt;">{{lang|und-Deva|च}}</span> ''ca'', <span style="font-size:14pt;">{{lang|und-Deva|ल}}</span> ''la'', and <span style="font-size:14pt;">{{lang|und-Deva|र}}</span> ''ra'', causing these second members to be shifted down and reduced in size. Thus <span style="font-size:14pt;">{{lang|und-Deva|श्व}}</span> ''śva'', <span style="font-size:14pt;">{{lang|und-Deva|श्न}}</span> ''śna'', <span style="font-size:14pt;">{{lang|und-Deva|श्च}}</span> ''śca'' <span style="font-size:14pt;">{{lang|und-Deva|श्ल}}</span> ''śla'', and <span style="font-size:14pt;">{{lang|und-Deva|श्र}}</span> ''śra''.
* <span style="font-size:14pt;">{{lang|und-Deva|र}}</span> ''r(a)'' as a first member takes the form of a curved upward dash above the final character or its ''ā-''diacritic. e.g. <span style="font-size:14pt;">{{lang|und-Deva|र्व}}</span> ''rva'', <span style="font-size:14pt;">{{lang|und-Deva|र्वा}}</span> ''rvā'', <span style="font-size:14pt;">{{lang|und-Deva|र्स्प}}</span> ''rspa'', <span style="font-size:14pt;">{{lang|und-Deva|र्स्पा}}</span> ''rspā''. As a final member with <span style="font-size:14pt;">{{lang|und-Deva|ट}}</span> ''ṭa'' <span style="font-size:14pt;">{{lang|und-Deva|ठ}}</span> ''ṭha'' <span style="font-size:14pt;">{{lang|und-Deva|ड}}</span> ''ḍa'' <span style="font-size:14pt;">{{lang|und-Deva|ढ}}</span> ''ḍha'' <span style="font-size:14pt;">{{lang|und-Deva|ड़}}</span> ''ṛa'' <span style="font-size:14pt;">{{lang|und-Deva|छ}}</span> ''cha'' it is two lines below the character, pointed downwards and apart. Thus <span style="font-size:14pt;">{{lang|und-Deva|ट्र}}</span> ''ṭra'' <span style="font-size:14pt;">{{lang|und-Deva|ठ्र}}</span> ''ṭhra'' <span style="font-size:14pt;">{{lang|und-Deva|ड्र}}</span> ''ḍra'' <span style="font-size:14pt;">{{lang|und-Deva|ढ्र}}</span> ''ḍhra'' <span style="font-size:14pt;">{{lang|und-Deva|ड़्र}}</span> ''ṛra'' <span style="font-size:14pt;">{{lang|und-Deva|छ्र}}</span> ''chra''. Elsewhere as a final member it is a diagonal stroke extending leftwards and down. e.g. <span style="font-size:14pt;">{{lang|und-Deva|क्र ग्र भ्र}}</span>. <span style="font-size:14pt;">{{lang|und-Deva|त}}</span> ''ta'' is shifted up to make <span style="font-size:14pt;">{{lang|und-Deva|त्र}}</span> ''tra''.
* As first members, remaining characters lacking vertical strokes such as <span style="font-size:14pt;">{{lang|und-Deva|द}}</span> ''d(a)'' and <span style="font-size:14pt;">{{lang|und-Deva|ह}}</span> ''h(a)'' may have their second member, reduced in size and lacking its horizontal stroke, placed underneath. <span style="font-size:14pt;">{{lang|und-Deva|क}}</span> ''k(a)'', <span style="font-size:14pt;">{{lang|und-Deva|छ}}</span> ''ch(a)'', and <span style="font-size:14pt;">{{lang|und-Deva|फ}}</span> ''ph(a)'' shorten their right hooks and join them directly to the following member.
* The conjuncts for ''{{IAST|kṣ}}'' and ''{{IAST|jñ}}'' are not clearly derived from the letters making up their components. The conjunct for ''{{IAST|kṣ}}'' is <span style="font-size:14pt;">{{lang|und-Deva|क्ष}}</span> (<span style="font-size:14pt;">{{lang|und-Deva|क्}}</span> + <span style="font-size:14pt;">{{lang|und-Deva|ष}}</span>) and for ''{{IAST|jñ}}'' it is <span style="font-size:14pt;">{{lang|und-Deva|ज्ञ}}</span> (<span style="font-size:14pt;">{{lang|und-Deva|ज्}}</span> + <span style="font-size:14pt;">{{lang|und-Deva|ञ}}</span>).

