===Accent marks===
{{Main|Vedic accent}}
The [[pitch accent]] of [[Vedic Sanskrit]] is written with various symbols depending on [[shakha]]. In the [[Rigveda]], ''anudātta'' is written with a bar below the line ({{lang|sa|◌॒}}), ''svarita'' with a stroke above the line ({{lang|sa|◌॑}}) while ''udātta'' is unmarked.

===Punctuation===
The end of a sentence or half-verse may be marked with the "{{lang|und-Deva|।}}" symbol (called a ''danda'', meaning "bar", or called a ''{{IAST|pūrṇa virām}}'', meaning "full stop/pause"). The end of a full verse may be marked with a double-''danda'', a "{{lang|und-Deva|॥}}" symbol. A comma (called an ''{{IAST|alpa virām}}'', meaning "short stop/pause") is used to denote a natural pause in speech.<ref>Unicode Consortium, The Unicode Standard, Version 3.0, Volume 1, {{ISBN|978-0201616330}}, Addison-Wesley, pages 221-223</ref><ref name=ijetr>[http://www.ijetr.org/finalpdf/1386305476.pdf Transliteration from Hindi Script to Meetei Mayek] Watham and Vimal (2013), IJETR, page 550</ref> Other punctuation marks such as colon, semi-colon, exclamation mark, dash, and question mark are currently in use in Devanagari script, matching their use in European languages.<ref>Michael Shapiro (2014), The Devanagari Writing System in ''A Primer of Modern Standard Hindi'', Motilal Banarsidass, {{ISBN|978-8120805088}}, page 26</ref>

===Old forms===
